Based in a recently expanded Mayfair gallery space, Beetles+Huxley hosts
 upwards of ten exhibitions per year. The gallery represents many of the
 world\'s most sought after and influential photographers, and also 
trades significantly on the secondary market – stocking work by 
photographic masters from Edward Weston to Irving Penn.


The gallery is popular amongst collectors for both its friendly, 
welcoming atmosphere and its engaging, academic approach to promoting 
photography. From the erudite exhibition catalogues that accompany each 
exhibition to regular curator-led museum tours and artist interviews the
 gallery is devoted to encouraging the wider appreciation of 
photographic history.


In January 2015 Beetles+Huxley was named a "Brand of Tomorrow" by the 
prestigious Walpole group in recognition of the gallery\'s ongoing 
promotion of photography in London.','Beetles And Huxley',2,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'3-5 Swallow Street W1B 4DE London',NULL,0,51.5093726,'3-5 Swallow Street W1B 4DE London',-0.137658900000019,'Monday - Saturday : 10:00 - 17:30',CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'www.beetlesandhuxley.com');
insert into venue values (NULL,'The name Belmacz was conceived by Julia Muggenburg to unite bel and maximum.
 It partially stands as homage to the iconic French jewellery designer 
Suzanne Belperron. Belmacz was founded by Julia Muggenburg in 2000 to 
show her one-of-a-kind gems. Today Belmacz has evolved into a truly 
unique space in which Julia Muggenburg alongside selected artists and 
friends, explores the aesthetics of modern life, and the ways in which a
 variety of art forms, from past and present, can inform each other.
 
Opposite Claridge’s in London’s Mayfair, 
located in a two-storey Regency building on Davies Street, Belmacz is a 
modern version of the ‘Wunderkammer’. By offering clients, friends and 
visitors displays of Julia Muggenburg’s unique precious jewels, 
contemporary art, ancient artefacts and objects of virtue.
 
Through its annual programme of solo and 
group exhibitions, and the dialogues it facilitates, Belmacz is a podium
 upon which emerging and established national and international artists 
are invited to explore some of the most pressing issues of our times. In
 2014 Julia was invited to present her unique vision at Nottingham 
Contemporary, one of the largest contemporary art centres in the UK, 
where she curated the exhibition Fourth Drawer Down, a reflection on the intersection between art and anthropology, drawing on her personal collection.
 
Born in Germany and trained in fine art in 
London’s Central Saint Martins, Julia Muggenburg created her first 
jewels to fulfil her need for sensuous, architectural and iconic 
objects. Rooted in ancient craft traditions yet boldly contemporary, 
Belmacz jewels evoke a twenty-first-century take on the status-affirming
 ceremonial adornments worn by tribal chiefs, patriarchs and paragons of
 style.
 
“Empowering primeval-modern ornaments for today’s cool, intellectual, urban warrior”
Vivienne Becker (Financial Times)
 
Redefining such universal forms, as the 
ring, the cuff, or the necklace, Belmacz pieces are Julia Muggenburg’s 
form of expressing the contemporary, refined spirit. Even a 
state-of-the-art Belmacz cache of balms, glosses, powders and eye 
colours with pure 24ct gold leaf has been conceived. These enduring 
Belmacz gems are created to enhance the wearer’s sense of empowerment, 
sense of self, strive to have a talismanic quality and impart a tangible
 sense of joy.
 ','Belmacz ',2,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'45 Davies Street W1K 4LX London',NULL,0,51.5124023,'45 Davies Street W1K 4LX London',-0.148401899999953,'Monday - Friday : 09:30 - 18:00, Saturday: 11:00 - 17:00 or by appointment',CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'www.belmacz.com');
insert into venue values (NULL,'Ben Brown Fine Arts opened its first location on Cork Street in the 
