We believe in the importance of creating a cultural space that presents new thinking and daring creativity, illuminates ideas, inspires understanding, and interrogates contemporary issues. Our vision is for a London audience with a more informed, engaged and critical understanding of Arab culture and society.','The Mosaic Rooms',2,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'A.M. Qattan Foundation SW5 0SW London',NULL,0,51.4949426,'A.M. Qattan Foundation SW5 0SW London',-0.195367799999985,'Monday - Friday : 10:00-18:00',CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'mosaicrooms.org');
insert into venue values (NULL,'The Muse gallery was established by artists, to support emerging contemporaries  by combining creative and commercial concepts under one roof.

Subject to a successful application, we also offer exhibition space to more established artists at a nominal commission. With limited slots per year, we look to our panel of affiliated artists and esteemed professionals to elect shows and offer comprehensive appraisals to those proposals still in need of refinement. 

Throughout the year, we also open our doors to community arts projects, musicians, film makers and live performers to fill the calendar with events from \'Sound art’ to ‘Cult film’ evenings and associated seminars.

Our residency program (only BA and MA graduates need apply) continues to offer a subsidised platform for candidates, with a group and solo show during their time with us. 

We work towards both public and private sector funding for our residents and visiting artists, with professional development working along side our team during visiting shows hosted throughout the year.

(AIR commissions are discretionary) 

Since established in 2003, we have continued to offer graduates and visiting artists improved conditions for arts practice and the exhibition of work and will endeavour to continue with \'artists for artists\' at the heart of our organisation.','The Muse',2,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'269 Portobello Road W11 1LR London',NULL,0,51.5178141,'269 Portobello Road W11 1LR London',-0.206744100000037,'Thursday - Sunday : 12:00 - 18:00',CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'www.themuseat269.com');
insert into venue values (NULL,'The Photographers\' Gallery is the largest public gallery in London dedicated to photography. From the latest emerging talent, to historical archives and established artists, we\'re the place to see photography in all its forms.','The Photographers Gallery',2,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'16 - 18 Ramillies Street W1F 7LW London',NULL,0,51.5149251,'16 - 18 Ramillies Street W1F 7LW London',-0.139046699999994,'Monday - Saturday : 10:00 - 18:00, Thursday : 10:00 - 20:00, Sunday : 11:30 - 18:00',CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'www.thephotographersgallery.org.uk');
insert into venue values (NULL,'The Queen\'s Gallery is a public art gallery at Buckingham Palace, home of the British monarch, in London. It exhibits works of art from the Royal Collection (those works owned by the King or Queen "in trust for the nation" rather than privately) on a rotating basis; about 450 works are on display at any one time.

The gallery is at the west front of the Palace, on the site of a chapel bombed during the Second World War, and first opened in 1962. Over the following 37 years it received 5 million visitors, until it was closed in 1999–2002 for extension work carried out by John Simpson. On 21 May 2002, the gallery was reopened by Elizabeth II to coincide with her Golden Jubilee. The extension added the current Doric entrance portico and several new rooms, more than tripling the size of the building.[1] It is open to the public for much of the year.','The Queens Gallery',2,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'Buckingham Palace SW1A 1AA London',NULL,0,51.501009,'Buckingham Palace SW1A 1AA London',-0.14158759999998,'Monday - Sunday : 9:30 - 16:30',CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'www.royalcollection.org.uk');
insert into venue values (NULL,' The Redfern Gallery was founded in September 1923 on the top floor of Redfern House at 27 Old Bond Street, London W1, as a small artists\' cooperative. It is now one of the longest-established dealers of Modern British and Contemporary art in London.

The founders were two wealthy individuals Arthur Knyvett-Lee and Anthony Maxtone Graham. A young New Zealander, Rex Nan Kivell, joined the gallery in 1925 and, in 1931, took control of the company. Notable exhibitions in these early years include a 1924 mixed exhibition which included the student work of Henry Moore and Barbara Hepworth, and in 1929, the first exhibition of British Linocuts, featuring prints by the Grosvenor School of Modern Art, particularly Sybil Andrews, Cyril Edward Power, and their instructor, Claude Flight.

In 1936 the gallery moved around the corner to larger premises at 20 Cork Street - just opposite the Burlington Arcade and behind the Royal Academy of Arts. The house which comprises 19/20 Cork Street was built in the early 18th Century. At that time it was the town house of John Montague, 4th Earl of Sandwich, and Redfern\'s main galleries are purportedly where the Earl used to play cards when he was in London. While the gallery does not have any street-facing windows, the Redfern is one of the few London galleries to benefit from skylights. In 1938, the Redfern organised the first large-scale retrospective of Christopher Wood\'s paintings at the New Burlington Galleries. Unlike many West End galleries, the Redfern was able to stay in operation during the Second World War; Eileen Agar, Corot, Eric Gill, Augustus John, Paul Nash, and Christopher Wood were just some of the artists exhibited during that period.

The 1960s saw a new generation of young British artists emerging, and the Redfern Gallery was no different. In 1963, Patrick Procktor had his first solo exhibition nearly sell-out before the opening evening; he would remain represented by the Redfern for the rest of his career. The gallery was also exhibiting young talent such as John Carter, David Hockney, Bryan Organ, David Oxtoby and Peter Sedgley.

Today the Redfern represents over 30 contemporary artists and artist\'s estates. It also has an extensive stock of modern and contemporary paintings, drawings, watercolours, sculpture and original prints. ','The Redfern Gallery',2,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'20 Cork Street W1S 3HL London',NULL,0,51.5100628,'20 Cork Street W1S 3HL London',-0.140916500000003,'Monday - Friday : 11:00 - 17:30, Saturday : 11:00 - 14:00',CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'www.redfern-gallery.com');
insert into venue values (NULL,'The Residence Gallery is a commercial and conceptual contemporary fine art venue based in London, UK. Founded in 2005 by artist/curator Ingrid Z, the gallery has seen a great deal of transformation from its underground roots in an abandoned Victorian mental hospital in Whitechapel and covert operation in the Verger’s Cottage at St. Mary of Eton Church in Hackney Wick. Now situated at Victoria Park Road E9, it’s mission remains strong; to challenge convention and promote a movement of cultural progression through fine art.

The gallery exhibits a wide range of media in often immersive-installation styled exhibitions. Exceptional London artists who have featured over the past 10 years in the gallery and at its international art fair stands (Pulse Miami and London Art Fair) are the key focus of our 2015 programme. They include Daryl Brown, Liam Ryan, Robert Hawkins, Alexander Heaton and Ben Gooding. Other artists of importance for whom The Residence Gallery has exhibited and remains connected with include Rckay Rax, Darren Coffield, Tasman Richardson, Declan Rooney, Brad Phillips, Jonas Ranson and Mike Ballard.

Director Ingrid Z graduated with an honours degree in fine art from York University in Toronto, Canada (2001). She co-founded and co-curated Toronto gallery West Wing Art Space (2000-2002) and has extensively worked with a number of international contemporary galleries and collectors. Ingrid relocated to London from Toronto in 2003, shortly thereafter she founded The Residence Gallery. ','The Residence Gallery',2,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'229 Victoria Park Rd E9 7HD London',NULL,0,51.5382711,'229 Victoria Park Rd E9 7HD London',-0.0435278999999582,'Thursday - Saturday : 11:00 - 18:00, Sunday : 12:00 - 17:00',CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'www.residence-gallery.com');
insert into venue values (NULL,'The RYDER is a new project space for contemporary art on Herald Street in East London. Concealed behind an industrial shutter, the space aims to provide a platform to support emerging and mid-career artists from around the world. During its first year, the exhibition program has had a strong focus on performance, video and installation, complemented by public talks and events to encourage dialogue and critical reflection.  

While current critical thinking frames contemporary art predominantly in terms of the multidisciplinary, specialisation is still commonplace. The RYDER bets on diversity, supporting the multiplicity that comes from an increasingly globalised society.','The Ryder',2,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'19a Herald Street E2 6JT London',NULL,0,51.5251689,'19a Herald Street E2 6JT London',-0.0559683999999834,'Wednesday - Saturday : 12:00 - 18:00',CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'www.theryderprojects.com');
insert into venue values (NULL,'We commission and produce art and discourse; providing an engaging, collaborative programme that challenges what art can be and do for a wide range of audiences, including art professionals and our local community.

Our programme focuses on collaborative and process-driven approaches to production be that art work, exhibitions, events, discussions, publications, knowledge and relationships. Through major commissions and smaller projects we work with artists and other practitioners who have not previously had significant exposure in London, often introducing international artists to London, and working in partnership with other individuals and organisations within our networks, both at home and abroad.

We also work closely with our local community through an aspect of the programme called Communal Knowledge, and have developed strong, long-term relationships with local groups and individuals who we bring together to work in partnership with artists on specific projects and commissions which feed into the programme as a whole.

Public events and workshops form part of these commissions, with a broader programme of publishing, research and events including discussions, screenings, panels, book launches and performances running alongside.

The Showroom was established in 1983 and in 2013 celebrated thirty years of supporting artists to stage their first solo shows in London and its role as a pivotal force in the development of contemporary art practice.

It was one of the first galleries in what is now a thriving East End art scene, but moved from its Bonner Road site in Bethnal Green to Penfold Street near Edgware Road in 2009. The first exhibition at Penfold Street was A Long Time Between Suns Part II, by The Otolith Group, which earned them a nomination for the Turner Prize 2010.

Other now well-known artists commissioned by The Showroom early in their careers include Marc Chaimowicz, Jim Lambie, Eva Rothschild, Mona Hatoum, Simon Starling, Rebecca Warren, Claire Barclay, Can Altay, Lawrence Abu Hamdan and Ciara Phillips (project nominated for the Turner Prize 2014).

The organisation has had four directors: Emily Pethick (2008–current), Kirsty Ogg (1998–2008), Kim Sweet (1992–1998) and David Thorp (1988–1992) and since 2009 its core staffing, while still small, has increased.

As well as supporting artists at the right moment in their careers, The Showroom has always played a role in developing discourse around contemporary art practices. This activity was expanded as a result of the move to Penfold Street and the directorship of Emily Pethick, and the organisation now programmes around 50 public events per year, almost all of which are free to access.','The Showroom',2,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'63 Penfold Street NW8 8PQ London',NULL,0,51.5237011,'63 Penfold Street NW8 8PQ London',-0.173328900000001,'Wednesday - Saturday : 12:00 - 18:00',CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'www.theshowroom.org');
insert into venue values (NULL,'The Stone Space is an independent gallery in Leytonstone that opened in October 2011 and occupies part of the ground floor of the Leytonstone Library building. It grew from the Leytonstone Arts Trail, an annual festival of visual art where artists display their work in a variety of venues around Leytonstone.

The Stone Space hosts a varied programme of exhibitions, not limited to a specific type of art, medium or group of artists and aims to champion artistic enquiry, recognise ability and give a platform to art that provokes thought and debate.

Exhibitions are held for a month and the gallery’s regular and ever popular private view evenings, that usually take place at the start of each exhibition, provide an important opportunity for social contact and networking amongst visitors, members of the local community and all involved with the gallery. Further information about the exhibition selection process and how to submit a proposal is available here.

The gallery receives very little funding, its activities are mainly self-funded by exhibitors and via commission on any works sold. The gallery is staffed by volunteers and is led by a group of volunteer organisers who plan the exhibition programme and oversee the management of the gallery.','The Stone Space',2,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'6 Church Lane E11 1HG London',NULL,0,51.568235,'6 Church Lane E11 1HG London',0.00911339999993288,'Thursday - Friday : 14:00 - 18:00, Saturday 10:00 - 17:00, Sunday 12:00 - 16:00',CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,'https://thestonespace.wordpress.com');
